{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:21:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:21:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15032"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15032"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116264"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7720"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98260"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"},{"type":"tags","id":"10547"},{"type":"tags","id":"10548"},{"type":"tags","id":"10549"},{"type":"tags","id":"10550"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18859"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116264"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe kidneys play a crucial role in maintaining acid-base balance through various mechanisms including hydrogen ion secretion, bicarbonate reabsorption, and ammonia production.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes renal compensation in acid-base disorders?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased hydrogen ion secretion occurs in respiratory alkalosis","Increased bicarbonate reabsorption occurs in respiratory alkalosis","Decreased ammonia production occurs in respiratory acidosis","Decreased hydrogen ion secretion occurs in metabolic acidosis","Increased alveolar ventilation occurs in metabolic alkalosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased hydrogen ion secretion occurs in respiratory alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E, the kidneys reduce H+ secretion to help retain acid and compensate for the alkalemia. This is a fair dinkum compensatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bicarbonate reabsorption occurs in respiratory alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because bicarbonate reabsorption actually decreases to help sort out the alkalemia. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased ammonia production occurs in respiratory acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is wrong as NH3 production goes up to help get rid of the excess acid. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased hydrogen ion secretion occurs in metabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since H+ secretion ramps up to help chuck out the excess acid. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased alveolar ventilation occurs in metabolic alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E is wrong because breathing actually slows down to hang onto CO2 and make acid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe kidneys compensate for acid-base dramas through three main mechanisms: modulation of H+ secretion, adjustment of bicarbonate reabsorption, and changes in ammonia production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The kidneys compensate for respiratory acidosis by increasing H+ secretion and NH3 production","In respiratory alkalosis, the kidneys decrease H+ secretion and bicarbonate reabsorption","Metabolic acidosis increases both H+ secretion and NH3 production in the proximal tubule"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98260"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15032"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98260"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T02:50:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T02:51:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7720"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116264"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"at